			<h2>Anatomy of a Modal</h2>
			
			<p>Modals are best suited to situations when you need to grab the user's attention or need user input (for example, deleting a document).</p>
			
			<img src="../../../docs/images/styleguide/sg-modal-example.png">
			
			<h3>Closing the modal (escape hatch)</h3>
			<p>Users can close the modal in the following ways:</p>
			<ul>
			<li>Close button</li>
			<li>Cancel button</li>
			<li>Escape key</li>
			<li>Click outside the window</li>
			</ul>
			
			<h3>Descriptive title</h3>
			<p>The title should give context to the user and outline the action they are about to perform.</p>
			
			<h3>Clear question</h3>
			<p>A simple, clear question should be presented to the user. This will clarify the action they are about to perform and give direction on what button they want to click. Questions should be kept as short and succinct and possible.</p>
			
			<h3>Buttons</h3>
			<p>Buttons should appear on the bottom left of the modal and there should be no more than 3 options presented to the user. One button should always be considered the 'primary' action and should use the Primary button styling.</p>
			<p>Button labels should have actionable, understandable names (this actually applies to a button in <b>any</b> instance). A simple Yes or No is too ambiguous. Instead, aim for labels like 'Delete file', 'Save claim' or 'Submit feedback', and of course, 'Cancel'.</p>
			<br>
			
			<hr>
			
			<h2>Placement</h2>
			
			<p>The goal with modal sizing is to keep context with the active page. On medium to large screens, a modal appears in the center of the page with a transparent shaded area masking the active page. On mobile devices (where screen space is at a premium), context is sacrificed for readability and a modal will fill the entire width of the screen. In either case, content should fit the modal - a scroll bar should not be needed.</p>

